# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: inventory-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:inventory-management/barcode] A **barcode** or **bar code** is a method of representing data in a visual, machine-readable symbolic form.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Initially, barcodes represented data by varying the widths, spacings and sizes of parallel lines.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] These barcodes, commonly referred to as linear or one-dimensional (1D), can be scanned by optical scanners known as barcode readers.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Later, two-dimensional (2D) variants were developed, using rectangles, dots, hexagons and other patterns, called *matrix codes* or *2D barcodes*.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Despite being often included as barcodes, these do not use bars as linear barcodes do.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] These can be read using purpose-built 2D optical scanners.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Both matrix codes and linear barcodes can also be read by a digital camera connected to a computer.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] After a photograph of the barcode is taken, software is used to analyze the image to deconstruct and decode the code.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] A mobile device with a built-in camera, such as a smartphone, can function as this type of barcode reader using specialized application software.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The barcode was invented by Norman Joseph Woodland and Bernard Silver and patented in the US in 1952.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The invention was based on Morse code that was extended to thin and thick bars.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] However, it took over twenty years before this invention became commercially successful.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] UK magazine *Modern Railways* December 1962 pages 387–389 record how British Railways had already perfected a barcode-reading system capable of correctly reading rolling stock travelling at 100 mph (160 km/h) with no mistakes.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] An early use of one type of barcode in an industrial context was sponsored by the Association of American Railroads in the late 1960s.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Developed by General Telephone and Electronics (GTE) and called KarTrak ACI (Automatic Car Identification), this scheme involved placing colored stripes in various combinations on steel plates which were affixed to the sides of railroad rolling stock.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Two plates were used per car, one on each side, with the arrangement of the colored stripes encoding information such as ownership, type of equipment, and identification number.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The plates were read by a trackside scanner located, for instance, at the entrance to a classification yard, while the car was moving past.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The project was abandoned after about ten years because the system proved unreliable after long-term use.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcodes became commercially successful after they were adopted to automate supermarket checkout systems, a task for which they have become almost universal.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The Uniform Grocery Product Code Council had chosen, in 1973, the barcode design developed by George Laurer.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Laurer's barcode, with vertical bars, printed better than the circular barcode developed by Woodland and Silver.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Their use has spread to many other tasks that are generically referred to as automatic identification and data capture (AIDC).
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The first successful system using barcodes was in the UK supermarket group Sainsbury's in 1972 using shelf-mounted barcodes which were developed by Plessey.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In June 1974, Marsh supermarket in Troy, Ohio used a scanner made by Photographic Sciences Corporation to scan the Universal Product Code (UPC) barcode on a pack of Wrigley's chewing gum.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] QR codes, a specific type of 2D barcode, rose in popularity in the second decade of the 2000s due to the growth in smartphone ownership.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Other systems have made inroads in the AIDC market, but the simplicity, universality and low cost of barcodes has limited the role of these other systems, particularly before technologies such as radio-frequency identification (RFID) became available.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In 1948, Bernard Silver, a graduate student at Drexel Institute of Technology in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, US overheard the president of the local food chain, Food Fair, asking one of the deans to research a system to automatically read product information during checkout.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Silver told his friend Norman Joseph Woodland about the request, and they started working on a variety of systems.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Their first working system used ultraviolet ink, but the ink faded too easily and was expensive.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Convinced that the system was workable with further development, Woodland left Drexel, moved into his father's apartment in Florida, and continued working on the system.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] His next inspiration came from Morse code, and he formed his first barcode from sand on the beach.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] He later decided that the system would work better if it were printed as a circle instead of a line, allowing it to be scanned in any direction.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] On 20 October 1949 Woodland and Silver filed a patent application for "Classifying Apparatus and Method", in which they described both the linear and bull's eye printing patterns, as well as the mechanical and electronic systems needed to read the code.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The patent was issued on 7 October 1952 as US Patent 2,612,994.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In 1951, Woodland moved to IBM and continually tried to interest IBM in developing the system.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The company eventually commissioned a report on the idea, which concluded that it was both feasible and interesting, but that processing the resulting information would require equipment that was some time off in the future.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] IBM offered to buy the patent, but the offer was not accepted.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Philco purchased the patent in 1962 and then sold it to RCA sometime later.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] During his time as an undergraduate, David Jarrett Collins worked at the Pennsylvania Railroad and became aware of the need to automatically identify railroad cars.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Immediately after receiving his master's degree from MIT in 1959, he started work at GTE Sylvania and began addressing the problem.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] He developed a system called *KarTrak* using blue, white and red reflective stripes attached to the side of the cars, encoding a four-digit company identifier and a six-digit car number.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Light reflected off the colored stripes was read by photomultiplier vacuum tubes.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The Boston and Maine Railroad tested the KarTrak system on their gravel cars in 1961.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The tests continued until 1967, when the Association of American Railroads (AAR) selected it as a standard, automatic car identification, across the entire North American fleet.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The installations began on 10 October 1967.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] However, the economic downturn and rash of bankruptcies in the industry in the early 1970s greatly slowed the rollout, and it was not until 1974 that 95% of the fleet was labeled.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] To add to its woes, the system was found to be easily fooled by dirt in certain applications, which greatly affected accuracy.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The AAR abandoned the system in the late 1970s, and it was not until the mid-1980s that they introduced a similar system, this time based on radio tags.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The railway project had failed, but a toll bridge in New Jersey requested a similar system so that it could quickly scan for cars that had purchased a monthly pass.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Then the US Post Office requested a system to track trucks entering and leaving their facilities.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] These applications required special retroreflector labels.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Finally, Kal Kan asked the Sylvania team for a simpler (and cheaper) version which they could put on cases of pet food for inventory control.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In 1967, with the railway system maturing, Collins went to management looking for funding for a project to develop a black-and-white version of the code for other industries.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] They declined, saying that the railway project was large enough, and they saw no need to branch out so quickly.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Collins then quit Sylvania and formed the Computer Identics Corporation.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] As its first innovations, Computer Identics moved from using incandescent light bulbs in its systems, replacing them with helium–neon lasers, and incorporated a mirror as well, making it capable of locating a barcode up to a meter (3 feet) in front of the scanner.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] This made the entire process much simpler and more reliable, and typically enabled these devices to deal with damaged labels, as well, by recognizing and reading the intact portions.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Computer Identics Corporation installed one of its first two scanning systems in the spring of 1969 at a General Motors (Buick) factory in Flint, Michigan.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The system was used to identify a dozen types of transmissions moving on an overhead conveyor from production to shipping.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The other scanning system was installed at General Trading Company's distribution center in Carlstadt, New Jersey to direct shipments to the proper loading bay.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In 1966 the National Association of Food Chains (NAFC) held a meeting on the idea of automated checkout systems.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] RCA, which had purchased the rights to the original Woodland patent, attended the meeting and initiated an internal project to develop a system based on the bullseye code.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The Kroger grocery chain volunteered to test it.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In the mid-1970s the NAFC established the Ad-Hoc Committee for U.S.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Supermarkets on a Uniform Grocery-Product Code to set guidelines for barcode development.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In addition, it created a symbol-selection subcommittee to help standardize the approach.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In cooperation with consulting firm, McKinsey & Co., they developed a standardized 11-digit code for identifying products.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The committee then sent out a contract tender to develop a barcode system to print and read the code.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The request went to Singer, National Cash Register (NCR), Litton Industries, RCA, Pitney-Bowes, IBM and many others.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] A wide variety of barcode approaches was studied, including linear codes, RCA's bullseye concentric circle code, starburst patterns and others.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In the spring of 1971 RCA demonstrated their bullseye code at another industry meeting.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] IBM executives at the meeting noticed the crowds at the RCA booth and immediately developed their own system.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] IBM marketing specialist Alec Jablonover remembered that the company still employed Woodland, and he established a new facility in Research Triangle Park to lead development.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In July 1972 RCA began an 18-month test in a Kroger store in Cincinnati.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcodes were printed on small pieces of adhesive paper, and attached by hand by store employees when they were adding price tags.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The code proved to have a serious problem; the printers would sometimes smear ink, rendering the code unreadable in most orientations.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] However, a linear code, like the one being developed by Woodland at IBM, was printed in the direction of the stripes, so extra ink would simply make the code "taller" while remaining readable.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] So on 3 April 1973 the IBM UPC was selected as the NAFC standard.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] IBM had designed five versions of UPC symbology for future industry requirements: UPC A, B, C, D, and E.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] NCR installed a testbed system at Marsh's Supermarket in Troy, Ohio, near the factory that was producing the equipment.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] On 26 June 1974, a 10-pack of Wrigley's Juicy Fruit gum was scanned, registering the first commercial use of the UPC.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In 1971 an IBM team was assembled for an intensive planning session, threshing out, 12 to 18 hours a day, how the technology would be deployed and operate cohesively across the system, and scheduling a roll-out plan.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] By 1973, the team were meeting with grocery manufacturers to introduce the symbol that would need to be printed on the packaging or labels of all of their products.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] There were no cost savings for a grocery to use it, unless at least 70% of the grocery's products had the barcode printed on the product by the manufacturer.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] IBM projected that 75% would be needed in 1975.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Economic studies conducted for the grocery industry committee projected over $40 million in savings to the industry from scanning by the mid-1970s.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Those numbers were not achieved in that time-frame and some predicted the demise of barcode scanning.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The usefulness of the barcode required the adoption of expensive scanners by a critical mass of retailers while manufacturers simultaneously adopted barcode labels.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Neither wanted to move first and results were not promising for the first couple of years, with *Business Week* proclaiming "The Supermarket Scanner That Failed" in a 1976 article.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Sims Supermarkets were the first location in Australia to use barcodes, starting in 1979.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In 1981 the United States Department of Defense adopted the use of Code 39 for marking all products sold to the United States military.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] This system, Logistics Applications of Automated Marking and Reading Symbols (LOGMARS), is still used by DoD and is widely viewed as the catalyst for widespread adoption of barcoding in industrial uses.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcodes are widely used around the world in many contexts.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In stores, UPC barcodes are pre-printed on most items other than fresh produce from a grocery store.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] This speeds up processing at check-outs and helps track items and also reduces instances of shoplifting involving price tag swapping, although shoplifters can now print their own barcodes.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcodes that encode a book's ISBN are also widely pre-printed on books, journals and other printed materials.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In addition, retail chain membership cards use barcodes to identify customers, allowing for customized marketing and greater understanding of individual consumer shopping patterns.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] At the point of sale, shoppers can get product discounts or special marketing offers through the address or e-mail address provided at registration.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcodes are widely used in healthcare and hospital settings, ranging from patient identification (to access patient data, including medical history, drug allergies, etc.) to creating SOAP notes with barcodes to medication management.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] They are also used to facilitate the separation and indexing of documents that have been imaged in batch scanning applications, track the organization of species in biology, and integrate with in-motion checkweighers to identify the item being weighed in a conveyor line for data collection.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] They can also be used to keep track of objects and people; they are used to keep track of rental cars, airline luggage, nuclear waste, express mail, and parcels.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcoded tickets (which may be printed by the customer on their home printer, or stored on their mobile device) allow the holder to enter sports arenas, cinemas, theatres, fairgrounds, and transportation, and are used to record the arrival and departure of vehicles from rental facilities.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] By verifying a barcoded ticket against a list of valid tickets, this can allow the identification of duplicate or fraudulent tickets more easily.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcodes are widely used in shop floor control applications software where employees can scan work orders and track the time spent on a job.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Some ERP, MRP and other inventory management software has built in support for barcode reading.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcodes can be used to track inventory more quickly than manually noting specific items.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcodes are also used in some kinds of non-contact 1D and 2D position sensors.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] A series of barcodes are used in some kinds of absolute 1D linear encoder.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The barcodes are packed close enough together that the reader always has one or two barcodes in its field of view.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] As a kind of fiducial marker, the relative position of the barcode in the field of view of the reader gives incremental precise positioning, in some cases with sub-pixel resolution.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The data decoded from the barcode gives the absolute coarse position.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Matrix codes can embed a hyperlink to a web page.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] A mobile device with a built-in camera might be used to read the pattern and browse the linked website, which can help a shopper find the best price for an item in the vicinity.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Since 2005, airlines use an IATA-standard 2D barcode on boarding passes (Bar Coded Boarding Pass (BCBP)), and since 2008 2D barcodes sent to mobile phones enable electronic boarding passes.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Some applications for barcodes have fallen out of use.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Artists have used barcodes in art, such as Scott Blake's Barcode Jesus, as part of the post-modernism movement.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The mapping between messages and barcodes is called a *symbology*.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The specification of a symbology includes the encoding of the message into bars and spaces, any required start and stop markers, the size of the quiet zone required to be before and after the barcode, and the computation of a checksum.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The first character is encoded using black bars of varying width.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The second character is then encoded by varying the width of the white spaces between these bars.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Thus, characters are encoded in pairs over the same section of the barcode.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Interleaved 2 of 5 is an example of this.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Stacked symbologies repeat a given linear symbology vertically.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The most common among the many 2D symbologies are matrix codes, which feature square or dot-shaped modules arranged on a grid pattern.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] 2D symbologies also come in circular and other patterns and may employ steganography, hiding modules within an image (for example, DataGlyphs).
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Linear symbologies are optimized for laser scanners, which sweep a light beam across the barcode in a straight line, reading a *slice* of the barcode light-dark patterns.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Scanning at an angle makes the modules appear wider, but does not change the width ratios.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Stacked symbologies are also optimized for laser scanning, with the laser making multiple passes across the barcode.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In the 1990s development of charge-coupled device (CCD) imagers to read barcodes was pioneered by Welch Allyn.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Imaging does not require moving parts, as a laser scanner does.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In 2007, linear imaging had begun to supplant laser scanning as the preferred scan engine for its performance and durability.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] 2D symbologies cannot be read by a laser, as there is typically no sweep pattern that can encompass the entire symbol.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] They must be scanned by an image-based scanner employing a CCD or other digital camera sensor technology.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The earliest, and still the cheapest, barcode scanners are built from a fixed light and a single photosensor that is manually moved across the barcode.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Computer-connected barcode scanners use a variety of interfaces transfer their data.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The oldest barcode scanners communicate over a serial connection using RS-232, which requires special software running on the computer to parsing incoming data from the scanner.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Many barcode scanners connect to a computer and send data to a computer as if the barcode's data had been typed on the keyboard, which requires no additional software.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] These scanners often took the form factor of a "keyboard wedge" and were interposed between a PS/2 or AT keyboard and the computer.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Most modern computer-connected barcode scanners connect via USB and appear as a human interface device which behaves like an additional keyboard to input data coming from a barcode.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] A wide range of hardware is manufactured for standalone barcode readers by manufacturers such as Datalogic, Intermec, HHP (Hand Held Products), Microscan Systems, Unitech, Metrologic, PSC, and PANMOBIL, and Zebra Technologies (previously Motorola Solutions, which was previously Symbol Technologies).
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Most modern smartphones are able to decode barcode using their built-in camera.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Google's mobile Android operating system can use their own Google Lens application to scan QR codes, or third-party apps like Barcode Scanner to read both one-dimensional barcodes and QR codes.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Google's Pixel devices can natively read QR codes inside the default Pixel Camera app.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Nokia's Symbian operating system featured a barcode scanner, while mbarcode is a QR code reader for the Maemo operating system.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In Apple iOS 11, the native camera app can decode QR codes and can link to URLs, join wireless networks, or perform other operations depending on the QR Code contents.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Other paid and free apps are available with scanning capabilities for other symbologies or for earlier iOS versions.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] With BlackBerry devices, the App World application can natively scan barcodes and load any recognized Web URLs on the device's Web browser.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Windows Phone 7.5 is able to scan barcodes through the Bing search app.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] However, these devices are not designed specifically for the capturing of barcodes.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] As a result, they do not decode nearly as quickly or accurately as a dedicated barcode scanner or portable data terminal.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] It is common for producers and users of bar codes to have a quality management system which includes verification and validation of bar codes.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcode verification examines the quality of the barcode in comparison to industry standards and specifications.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcode verifiers are primarily used by businesses that print and use barcodes.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Any trading partner in the supply chain can test barcode quality.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] It is important to verify a barcode to ensure that any reader in the supply chain can successfully interpret a barcode with a low error rate.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Retailers levy large penalties for non-compliant barcodes that they receive.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] These chargebacks can reduce a barcode manufacturer's revenue by 2% to 10%.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] A barcode verifier works the way a reader does, but instead of simply decoding a barcode, a verifier performs a series of tests.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] These include several measurements of different contrast parameters, proper spacing of elements, and ability to be decoded, including when errors are introduced.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In 2D barcodes, uniformity against an ideal grid is also measured.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Compared with a reader, the measurement must be repeatable and consistent.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Doing so requires constant conditions such as distance, illumination angle, sensor angle and verifier aperture.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Based on the verification results, the production process can be adjusted to print higher quality barcodes.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Bar code validation may include evaluations after use for reliability against sunlight, abrasion, impact, and moisture.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcode verifier standards are defined by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), in ISO/IEC 15426-1 (linear) or ISO/IEC 15426-2 (2D).
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The current international barcode quality specification is ISO/IEC 15416 (linear) and ISO/IEC 15415 (2D).
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The European Standard EN 1635 has been withdrawn and replaced by ISO/IEC 15416.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The original U.S. barcode quality specification was ANSI X3.182.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] As of 2011 the ISO workgroup JTC1 SC31 was developing a Direct Part Marking (DPM) quality standard: ISO/IEC TR 29158.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In point-of-sale management, barcode systems can provide detailed up-to-date information on the business, accelerating decisions and with more confidence.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Besides sales and inventory tracking, barcodes are very useful in logistics and supply chain management.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Barcode scanners are relatively low cost and extremely accurate compared to key-entry, with only about 1 substitution error in 15,000 to 36 trillion characters entered.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The exact error rate depends on the type of barcode.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] A first generation, "one dimensional" barcode that is made up of lines and spaces of various widths or sizes that create specific patterns.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] 2D barcodes consist of bars, but use both dimensions for encoding.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] A *matrix code* or a *2D code* is a two-dimensional visual method to represent information.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] It can represent more data per unit area than a one-dimensional barcode.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Various different patterns are used to encode data.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In architecture, a building in Lingang New City by German architects Gerkan, Marg and Partners incorporates a barcode design, as does a shopping mall called *Shtrikh-kod* (Russian for *barcode*) in Narodnaya ulitsa ("People's Street") in the Nevskiy district of St.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In media, in 2011, the National Film Board of Canada and ARTE France launched a web documentary entitled *Barcode.tv*, which allows users to view films about everyday objects by scanning the product's barcode with their iPhone camera.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In professional wrestling, the WWE stable D-Generation X incorporated a barcode into their entrance video, as well as on a T-shirt.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] In video games, the protagonist of the *Hitman* video game series has a barcode tattoo on the back of his head; QR codes can also be scanned in a side mission in *Watch Dogs*.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] The 2018 videogame *Judgment* features QR Codes that protagonist Takayuki Yagami can photograph with his phone camera.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] These are mostly to unlock parts for Yagami's Drone.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Some companies integrate custom designs into barcodes on their consumer products without impairing their readability.
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Television host Phil Donahue described barcodes as a "corporate plot against consumers".
[src:inventory-management/barcode] Old Believers (a separation of the Russian Orthodox Church) and some Christian fundamentalists believe barcodes are a manifestation of the Number of the beast.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] The EOQ indicates the optimal number of units to order to minimize the total cost associated with the purchase, delivery, and storage of a product.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] EOQ applies only when demand for a product is constant over a period of time (such as a year) and each new order is delivered in full when inventory reaches zero.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] There is a fixed cost for each order placed, regardless of the quantity of items ordered; an order is assumed to contain only one type of inventory item.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] There is also a cost for each unit held in storage, commonly known as holding cost, sometimes expressed as a percentage of the purchase cost of the item.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Although the EOQ formulation is straightforward, factors such as transportation rates and quantity discounts factor into its real-world application.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] The required parameters to the solution are the total demand for the year, the purchase cost for each item, the fixed cost to place the order for a single item and the storage cost for each item per year.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Note that the number of times an order is placed will also affect the total cost, though this number can be determined from the other parameters.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Q* is independent of P; it is a function of only K, D, h.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] If we check the total cost for any order quantity other than 400(=EOQ), we will see that the cost is higher.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] This illustrates that the economic order quantity is always in the best interests of the firm.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] An important extension to the EOQ model is to accommodate quantity discounts.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] There are two main types of quantity discounts: (1) all-units and (2) incremental.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] In order to find the optimal order quantity under different quantity discount schemes, one should use algorithms; these algorithms are developed under the assumption that the EOQ policy is still optimal with quantity discounts.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] (2017) establish this optimality and fully characterize the (s,S) optimality within the EOQ setting under general cost structures.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] In presence of a strategic customer, who responds optimally to discount schedules, the design of an optimal quantity discount scheme by the supplier is complex and has to be done carefully.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] This is particularly so when the demand at the customer is itself uncertain.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] An interesting effect called the "reverse bullwhip" takes place where an increase in consumer demand uncertainty actually reduces order quantity uncertainty at the supplier.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Several extensions can be made to the EOQ model, including backordering costs and multiple items.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] where s is the number of backorders when order quantity Q is delivered and $\lambda$ is the rate of demand.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] In the first case the optimal lot is given by the classic EOQ formula, in the second case an order is never placed and minimum yearly cost is given by $\pi \lambda$ .
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] If $\pi >{\sqrt {\frac {2AIC}{\lambda }}}=\delta$ or $\pi \lambda >K_{w}$ $s^{*}=0$ is optimal, if $\pi <\delta$ then there shouldn't be any inventory system.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] If there are backorders, the reorder point is: $r_{h}^{*}=\mu -mQ^{*}-s^{*}$ ; with m being the largest integer $m\leq {\frac {\tau }{T}}$ and μ the lead time demand.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Additionally, the economic order interval can be determined from the EOQ and the economic production quantity model (which determines the optimal production quantity) can be determined in a similar fashion.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] A version of the model, the Baumol-Tobin model, has also been used to determine the money demand function, where a person's holdings of money balances can be seen in a way parallel to a firm's holdings of inventory.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Malakooti (2013) has introduced the multi-criteria EOQ models where the criteria could be minimizing the total cost, Order quantity (inventory), and Shortages.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] A version taking the time-value of money into account was developed by Trippi and Lewin.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Another important extension of the EOQ model is to consider items with imperfect quality.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Salameh and Jaber (2000) were the first to study the imperfect items in an EOQ model very thoroughly.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] They consider an inventory problem in which the demand is deterministic and there is a fraction of imperfect items in the lot and are screened by the buyer and sold by them at the end of the circle at discount price.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] He suggests that a system-based implementation would be beneficial where the number of stock-keeping units is over around 2000.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Annual updating of data and formulae are recommended.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] A hybrid system would involve downloading data into a spreadsheet for calculation purposes and then re-applying this data within the inventory system.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] The EOQ model and its sister, the economic production quantity model (EPQ), have been criticised for "their restrictive set[s] of assumptions.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Guga and Musa make use of the model for an Albanian business case study and conclude that the model is "perfect theoretically, but not very suitable from the practical perspective of this firm".
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] However, James Cargal notes that the formula was developed when business calculations were undertaken "by hand", or using logarithmic tables or a slide rule.
[src:inventory-management/economic-order-quantity] Use of spreadsheets and specialist software allows for more versatility in the use of the formula and adoption of "assumptions which are more realistic" than in the original model.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] An extension of inventory control is the inventory control system.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] This may come in the form of a technological system and its programmed software used for managing various aspects of inventory problems, or it may refer to a methodology (which may include the use of technological barriers) for handling loss prevention in a business.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] The inventory control system allows for companies to assess their current state concerning assets, account balances, and financial reports.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] An inventory control system is used to keep inventories in a desired state while continuing to adequately supply customers, and its success depends on maintaining clear records on a periodic or perpetual basis.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Inventory management software often plays an important role in the modern inventory control system, providing timely and accurate analytical, optimization, and forecasting techniques for complex inventory management problems.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Through this functionality, a business may better detail what has sold, how quickly, and at what price, for example.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Reports could be used to predict when to stock up on extra products around a holiday or to make decisions about special offers, discontinuing products, and so on.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] A new trend in inventory management is to label inventory and assets with a QR Code, which can then be read with smartphones to keep track of inventory count and movement.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] These new systems are especially useful for field service operations, where an employee needs to record inventory transaction or look up inventory stock in the field, away from the computers and hand-held scanners.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] The control of inventory involves managing the physical quantities as well as the costing of the goods as they flow through the supply chain.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] The calculation can be done for different periods.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] If the calculation is done on a monthly basis, then it is referred to as the periodic method.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] ADD Stock at beginning of period ADD Stock purchased during the period AVERAGE total cost by total qty to arrive at the Average Cost of Goods for the period.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] This Average Cost Price is applied to all movements and adjustments in that period.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Ending stock in qty is arrived at by Applying all the changes in qty to the Available balance.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Multiplying the stock balance in qty by the Average cost gives the Stock cost at the end of the period.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Using the perpetual method, the calculation is done upon every purchase transaction.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Thus, the calculation is the same based on the periodic calculation whether by period (periodic) or by transaction (perpetual).
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] The only difference is the 'periodicity' or scope of the calculation.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] In practice, the daily averaging has been used to closely approximate the perpetual method.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Inventory control systems have advantages and disadvantages, based on what style of system is being run.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Just-in-time inventory (JIT), vendor managed inventory (VMI) and customer managed inventory (CMI) are a few of the popular models being employed by organizations looking to have greater stock management control.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] JIT is a model that attempts to replenish inventory for organizations when the inventory is required.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] The model attempts to avoid excess inventory and its associated costs.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] As a result, companies receive inventory only when the need for more stock is approaching.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] VMI (vendor managed inventory) and (co-managed inventory) are two business models that adhere to the JIT inventory principles.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] VMI gives the vendor in a vendor/customer relationship the ability to monitor, plan and control inventory for their customers.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Customers relinquish the order making responsibilities in exchange for timely inventory replenishment that increases organizational efficiency.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] CMI allows the customer to order and control their inventory from their vendors/suppliers.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Both VMI and CMI benefit the vendor as well as the customer.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-control] Vendors see a significant increase in sales due to increased inventory turns and cost savings realized by their customers, while customers realize similar benefits.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] Inventory management software typically includes functions for monitoring stock quantities, recording receipts and issues, and supporting replenishment decisions.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] Common functions include maintaining stock records across one or more locations, tracking goods as they move between suppliers, warehouses, and retail sites, and supporting warehouse activities such as receiving, picking, packing, and shipping.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] Many inventory systems support the use of a reorder point, that is, a stock level at which replenishment should be initiated.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] Reorder-point methods are part of broader inventory-control practice concerned with determining when to replenish stock and in what quantity.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] Inventory systems commonly identify items through barcodes, serial numbers, lot numbers, or similar markers.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] More recent systems may also use radio-frequency identification (RFID), networked sensors, and other automated identification technologies to improve traceability and reduce manual data entry.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] The Universal Product Code (UPC) was adopted as a standard in 1973, and the first retail scan of a UPC-marked product took place in June 1974 at a Marsh supermarket in Troy, Ohio.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] The spread of barcode systems made machine-readable stock records more practical for retailers and later for other sectors.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] The increasing availability of personal computers and business software in the early 1980s also made computerized record-keeping more accessible.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] Database, spreadsheet, and other business applications became more widely available on relatively inexpensive hardware, making software-based inventory records increasingly practical for firms that had previously relied on manual systems.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] More recent inventory management systems have incorporated technologies such as barcode scanning, RFID, and the Internet of things (IoT), while also facing integration challenges in multi-location and enterprise settings.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] In manufacturing, inventory management software is often used together with production planning and enterprise resource planning (ERP) systems.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] Such systems may support material planning, bills of materials, production activity control, and related functions used to coordinate raw materials, work in process, and finished goods.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] Inventory management software may be installed locally or delivered as software as a service.
[src:inventory-management/inventory-management-software] In larger organizations, inventory functions are often integrated with wider transaction-processing or ERP systems that link sales, production, warehousing, finance, and logistics.
[src:inventory-management/stock-keeping-unit] In inventory management, a **stock keeping unit** (abbreviated as **SKU**, pronounced *es-kay-YOU* or *SKEW*) is the unit of measure in which the stocks of a material are managed.
[src:inventory-management/stock-keeping-unit] When a business records the inventory of its stock, it counts the quantity it has of each unit, or SKU.
[src:inventory-management/stock-keeping-unit] SKU can also refer to a unique identifier or code, sometimes represented via a barcode for scanning and tracking, which refers to the particular stock keeping unit.
[src:inventory-management/stock-keeping-unit] These identifiers are not regulated or standardized.
[src:inventory-management/stock-keeping-unit] When a company receives items from a vendor, it has a choice of maintaining the vendor's SKU or creating its own.
[src:inventory-management/stock-keeping-unit] This makes them distinct from Global Trade Item Number (GTIN), which are standard, global tracking units.
[src:inventory-management/stock-keeping-unit] The Universal Product Code (UPC), European Article Number (EAN), and Australian Product Number (APN) are special cases of GTINs.
[src:inventory-management/stock-keeping-unit] SKU is also used in software and software as a service (SaaS), including cloud computing.
[src:inventory-management/stock-keeping-unit] Cloud service providers such as Google Cloud Platform present different purchasable variations of the product or service as SKUs.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] A **warehouse management system** (**WMS**) is a set of policies and processes intended to organise the work of a warehouse or distribution centre, and ensure that such a facility can operate efficiently and meet its objectives.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] The core function of a warehouse management system is to record the arrival and departure of inventory.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Software which fulfils this function can offer features like recording the precise location of stock within the warehouse, optimising the use of available space, or coordinating tasks for maximum efficiency.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] In the 20th century, the term 'warehouse management information system' was often used to distinguish software that fulfils this function from theoretical systems.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Some smaller facilities may use spreadsheets or physical media like pen and paper to document their processes and activities, and this too can be considered a WMS.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] However, in contemporary usage, the term overwhelmingly refers to computer systems.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] More complex warehouse management systems tend to include specialised features designed for specific industries or types of facility, while legacy enterprise software vendors aim to offer as many of these features as possible in a ‘one-size-fits-all’ solution, which may be available as modules.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] An **advanced WMS** can analyse capacity and stock levels, and perhaps track how much time and labour is spent on different activities.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] This allows it to generate data that measures efficiency and suggest ways to improve it.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Outside of East Asia, Most WMS's in use today fall into this category.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] At this level, the duties of the WMS may begin to overlap with or supersede those of a Warehouse Control System or Warehouse Execution System.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] A **controlled WMS** can exchange data with other systems, in order to take into account information from outside the warehouse (e.g.: manufacturing needs, customer orders, transportation) when planning activities, and vice versa.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] A key example of this is the integration with fleet digitalization platforms, where the WMS can receive real-time data about inbound and outbound trucks from their on-board GPS tracking units via API integrations.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] A controlled WMS may also obtain feedback from automation or IoT devices, and may continuously simulate or test strategies for improving operations, perhaps using machine learning.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] An **autonomous WMS**can independently optimize warehouse operations using artificial intelligence, predictive analytics, and real-time automation.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] At this level, the system continuously evaluates inventory flow, labor allocation, equipment usage, and delivery schedules to make adaptive operational decisions with minimal human intervention.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] An autonomous WMS may integrate with robotic picking systems, autonomous mobile robots, digital twins, and cloud-based analytics platforms to improve efficiency and resilience.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] It can also predict disruptions, recommend corrective actions, and dynamically adjust workflows based on changing supply chain conditions.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] A WMS can either be hosted locally or installed on the cloud, allowing the WMS to be accessed from anywhere online.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Local WMS software has historically been offered through a perpetual licence, giving organisations the permanent right to install it on their own on-premises servers, typically alongside a fixed period of updates and technical support which may be renewed at additional cost.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] As with many types of enterprise software, this provision model is gradually being replaced by hosted subscription services.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Legacy enterprise software vendors typically offer both models, but incentivise their customers to move to the cloud.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] A WMS may be a standalone product, or can be a module or category of modules within a larger Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) system, Shipping or Inventory Management Software, or Supply Chain Management System (SCMS).
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] There may be surcharges when adding agencies or workers.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Installation type does not affect the level of functionality that may be achieved by a WMS, so long as sufficient computing power is provisioned and data is successfully synchronised with other systems.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Many **Enterprise Resource Planning** systems include a warehouse management module or set of modules.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] The core logic of an ERP system is transactional in nature; its purpose is to connect operational and commercial data to accounting and financial decision-making.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] As a result, its warehouse modules tend to focus on the metrics that are immediately and obviously relevant from a financial point of view, and tend to lack the sophistication of advanced WMS's.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Integrated **Supply Chain Management** software packages tend to bring together warehouse management with transportation management and additional functionality.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Unlike ERP systems, these systems usually focus on operational needs.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] However, like ERP systems they tend to lack the depth and configurability of a specialised WMS.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] The terms **Warehouse Control** and **Warehouse Execution** systems are sometimes used interchangeably with each other and with warehouse management systems.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] However, a WCS traditionally manages motorised equipment such as conveyor belts, as may be found in facilities handling high-volume, low-variety materials.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] As automation equipment has grown more sophisticated, it has been employed in more complex facilities, giving rise to WES nomenclature for systems that integrate advanced controls and WMS capabilities.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] As more features are added to each side, the distinction between a high-end WES and WMS blurs.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] The authors of Warehouse Science note that “there are over 300 WMS vendors in the US alone.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Warehouse management systems are typically legacy from Y2K investments in enterprise software, and are continually revised in various (possibly defunct) programming languages on top of existing systems over the years.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] This can make a WMS inflexible and difficult to maintain.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Researchers from the Business School at Erasmus University Rotterdam have described a standard WMS as forcing compromises between the abilities of the system and the way the warehouse wants to operate, which may have serious consequences for warehouse performance.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Meanwhile, demands on warehouses are growing in an increasingly competitive global marketplace.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Customizing WMSs can be costly—depending on the software, each customization can turn into a reimplementation.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] More complex software can also be more difficult for employees to use, leading to hire training costs.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Many researchers and analysts have pointed out that receiving operations, which account for about 17% of warehouse operating costs, are an area where contemporary WMSs tend to fall short.
[src:inventory-management/warehouse-management-system] Bottlenecks particularly occur in pre-scheduling and communications with external carriers, customers, and suppliers.
